ctory (database, secrets, artifacts) survives every update and rollback."],[1186,"`RUNYARD_HUB_BOOTSTRAP_TOKEN`"],[1178,"`RUNYARD_HUB_DATA_DIR`"],[1180,"`RUNYARD_HUB_DB`"],[1188,"`RUNYARD_HUB_INSTANCE_NAME`"],[1182,"`RUNYARD_HUB_SESSION_SECRET`"],[1195,"`RUNYARD_HUB_TOKEN`"],[1193,"`RUNYARD_HUB_URL`"],[1226,"`RUNYARD_HUB_URL` / `RUNYARD_HUB_TOKEN` environment variables\n(legacy `SMITHERS_HUB_URL` / `SMITHERS_HUB_TOKEN` and `HUB_URL` / `HUB_TOKEN`\nstill work)"],[1220,"`runyard-mcp` is a stdio Model Context Protocol\nserver that ships with the Runyard CLI. It runs locally next to your AI client\n(Claude Code, Claude Desktop, Codex, Cursor, and others), and translates every\ntool call into an authenticated HTTP request against your Hub. No workflow\nlogic runs in the MCP server itself — it is a thin, faithful client of the\nHTTP API."],[1206,"`runyard.sqlite` — the SQLite database (runs, workflows, tokens, schedules,\napprovals, encrypted secrets)"],[1291,"`sandbox-smoke`"],[1300,"`scripts/release-train.mjs` gives operators (and the deployment watchdog) machine-readable release state:"],[79,"`search_knowledge`"],[1184,"`SECRETS_ENC_KEY`"],[1209,"`session-secret.txt` — the persisted dev session secret when none is provided"],[569,"`set_secret`"],[680,"`shipped`"],[102,"`side_effect`"],[1043,"`side_effect`"],[291,"`skipped`"],[1443,"`slug`"],[739,"`slug`, `name`, `description`, `category`, `keywords`"],[1203,"`SMITHERS_RUNNER_CONCURRENCY`"],[1199,"`SMITHERS_RUNNER_LOCATION`"],[1201,"`SMITHERS_RUNNER_NAME` / `SMITHERS_RUNNER_TAGS`"],[1197,"`SMITHERS_WORKSPACE`"],[264,"`static-publish`"],[181,"`succeeded`"],[283,"`succeeded`"],[438,"`succeeded`"],[1108,"`tail` emits `{ts, kind, source, payload}` lines built from status transitions,\nevents, and artifacts, polling every 2 seconds with a `since` cursor — pipe it\ninto `jq` or downstream tooling."],[1059,"`TELEGRAM_APPROVAL_CHAT_ID`"],[1061,"`TELEGRAM_APPROVAL_USER_IDS`"],[1057,"`TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN`"],[1065,"`TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID` / `TELEGRAM_THREAD_ID`"],[1063,"`TELEGRAM_WEBHOOK_SECRET`"],[1288,"`test`"],[1395,"`timed_out`"],[1052,"`timeoutMs` is clamped to between 1 second and 30 days."],[668,"`triaged`"],[719,"`unlink_work_item_run`"],[68,"`update_agent`"],[204,"`update_board`"],[85,"`update_knowledge`"],[533,"`update_schedule`"],[76,"`update_skill`"],[710,"`update_work_item`"],[772,"`update_workflow`"],[303,"`upsert_hook`"],[306,"`validate_hook`"],[796,"`validate_workflow_package`"],[270,"`vercel-preview`"],[428,"`waiting_approval`"],[178,"`waiting_approval` / `paused` / `budget_exceeded`"],[179,"`waiting`"],[674,"`waiting`"],[268,"`webhook`"],[627,"`whoami`"],[1414,"`workflow_bundle_missing` / `workflow_source_missing` — the definition references source that is not published; send source bytes via `update_workflow`."],[1413,"`workflow_disabled`, `workflow_not_found` — an admin can re-enable via `PATCH /api/workflows/{id}`."],[98,"`workflow_gate`"],[1035,"`workflow_gate` (mid-run engine gate)"],[1459,"`workflow.engine`"],[1463,"`workflow.language`"],[1461,"`workflow.source`"],[749,"`workflow`"],[8,"<Card title=\"Concepts\" href=\"./concepts\" description=\"Workflows, runs, runners, approvals, and the Hub's durable record.\" />"],[9,"<Card title=\"HTTP API\" href=\"./guides/api\" description=\"Drive Runyard from any language with bearer-token auth and openapi.json.\" />"],[10,"<Card title=\"MCP\" href=\"./guides/mcp\" description=\"Connect AI agents to your Hub with the runyard-mcp server.\" />"],[7,"<Card title=\"Quickstart\" href=\"./quickstart\" description=\"Install the Hub, start a runner, and run your first workflow.\" />"],[13,"1\\. Install the Hub"],[992,"10 / minute"],[14,"2\\. Sign in with the bootstrap token"],[15,"3\\. Install the CLI and log in"],[994,"30 / minute"],[1185,"32-byte key (base64/hex) for the encrypted secrets store. Keep it safe — rotating it makes stored secrets unreadable"],[16,"4\\. Start a runner"],[1373,"401 / 403 responses"],[17,"5\\. Run the hello workflow"],[18,"6\\. Watch the run and read the results"],[996,"60 / minute"],[998,"60 / minute"],[155,"A **board** is a durable, configured view over work items: lane definitions in operator language, an optional project scope, and the workflows it suggests launching from tickets. Boards make the Work surface (`/app#work`) a **software factory**: tickets are the durable asks, workflows execute them, and linked runs move tickets across the board as they progress."],[260,"A **post-run hook profile** is an admin-authored recipe for an optional side effect — publishing static output, pushing a work branch, calling a webhook — that runs *after* a run has produced its verified artifacts and its gates have passed. Hooks separate \"the work succeeded\" from \"the side effect happened\": callers opt in per run, and hook outcomes never rewrite a run's status."],[425,"A **run** is a single execution of a workflow with a JSON input. Runs are created from the API, MCP, web app, CLI, a schedule, or a workflow endpoint; a runner claims each queued run and executes it, streaming events, logs, and artifacts back to the Hub as the durable record."],[382,"A **runner** is a machine that executes runs. Runners run the Runyard runner process, which claims queued runs from the Hub and executes each workflow via the **Smithers engine** (`smithers up <workflow> --input <json>`), spawning the local agent CLI as the worker. Nothing is faked: the agent runs on the runner's machine, and the Hub is the durable record — events stream back as run events, and outputs and traces are uploaded as artifacts."],[508,"A **schedule** runs a workflow automatically: either recurring on a **cron** cadence or once at a fixed **runAt** timestamp. Each fire creates a completely ordinary run with the schedule's stored input — it appears in run lists, honors the workflow's approval policy, and is executed by whatever runner matches."],[659,"A **work item*&#x2A; (ticket) is the durable unit of company work: &#x2A;\"Make pause/resume fully supported\"&#x2A;, &#x2A;\"Fix the flaky release gate\"*. It is deliberately distinct from the two execution concepts:"],[757,"A **workflow package** is a portable `.runyard-workflow.json` file for moving a workflow between Hubs. Exports contain source bytes, metadata, requirements, and content/workflow hashes — never secret values. Imports publish the source as a new immutable bundle and create the workflow **disabled by default**, so an admin can configure and preflight it locally before enabling it. `validate` and `preview` let you check a package without writing anything."],[735,"A **workflow** is the unit of the Runyard catalog: a named, versioned definition of something an agent can do. Each workflow has a slug, a display name and description, input/output schemas, and a source program that the runner executes. In older code and database tables the same object is called a *capability* — that is the legacy/internal synonym; user-facing surfaces say workflow."],[112,"A card's `status` is only ever `pending` or `resolved`. What was decided and by what live in separate fields:"],[1049,"A creator can make a card timed by supplying `timeoutMs` or `timeoutAt`, optionally with a `fallback` decision (`approve` or `reject`) — via `POST /api/approvals` or the `create_approval` MCP tool:"],[679,"A deliverable exists and needs inspection."],[1302,"A deployed Hub checks the public GitHub Releases API passively (outbound-only, `UPDATE_CHECK_ENABLED`, default on) and shows admins an update badge."],[293,"A failed hook never rewrites a successful run into a failed one: the run keeps its own status and the hook results ride in the run output, aggregated into one headline hook status. `POST /api/hooks/{slug}/validate` is the admin dry-run: it reports `hook_config_required` with missing secret *names* only."],[988,"A few endpoints are rate-limited per client IP (over the limit returns `429`):"],[103,"A gated side effect asking permission before it runs."],[145,"A held run is cancelled, never failed."],[309,"A map of the core Runyard concepts and how they fit together."],[839,"A metered, resumable run end to end:"],[1434,"A minimal, real example"],[606,"A normal person or agent: read everything, run workflows, decide approvals. No admin or runner rights."],[1387,"A quality gate (tests, lint, typecheck, build, eval) failed inside the workflow."],[1378,"A queued run means no runner has claimed it — either no runner is online, or none matches the run's required tags / requested location (`local` vs `vps`/`remote`)."],[661,"a run is **one execution attempt** of a workflow."],[1370,"A run is in `waiting_approval`"],[1369,"A run is stuck in `queued`"],[554,"A run receives the union of:"],[469,"A run request may include `responseEndpoint: {type: \"http\" | \"telegram\", config}` so the terminal-state reply is delivered to the caller when the run finishes. Delivery state is reported in `responseEndpoints[]` on `GET /api/runs/{id}`; polling that endpoint remains the canonical fallback."],[1379,"A runner is considered offline after \\~30 seconds without a heartbeat. If the runner should be online, check its service logs on the runner host:"],[1147,"A running Hub also serves its own **client** install script at\n`https://hub.example.com/install.sh` (plus the CLI tarball at `/cli.tgz`). That\none installs the `runyard` CLI and `runyard-mcp` on a workstation — see\nthe CLI guide."],[2,"A self-hosted control plane for agent runs — workflows in, durable runs, logs, artifacts, and approvals out."],[224,"A specific artifact."],[584,"A token carries one or more scopes; each endpoint declares which scopes may call it."],[334,"A usage record is one observed model call:"],[662,"A work item can use one workflow, many workflows, or none yet. Many runs can attach to one work item; a run belongs to at most one work item, and old runs can stay unlinked. Crucially, **there is no failed ticket state** — run failures are execution facts, not ticket verdicts. A failed linked run parks its ticket in `blocked` with an explicit reason (see Boards → Runs move tickets); humans and agents can always re-park or retry."],[736,"A workflow definition carries:"],[56,"A workflow definition declares `requiredAgents` and `requiredSkills` as lists of catalog slugs; `describe_workflow` reports them alongside the schemas so a caller can see what a workflow depends on before running it. Workflow package exports record these requirements, and import preview reports whether the target Hub satisfies them."],[660,"a workflow is a reusable **recipe**;"],[99,"A workflow paused at a gate; the decision releases or denies that step."],[389,"A workflow's `requiredRunnerTags` must all be present on the runner."],[976,"Abandon the negotiation"],[1265,"Admin & updates"],[1417,"Admin actions (creating workflows, secrets, tokens, schedules) need `admin`; running workflows needs `api` or `mcp`; the runner protocol needs `runner`. Ask a Hub admin for a token with the right scopes."],[248,"Admin and setup views."],[307,"Admin readiness dry-run."],[1110,"Admin-scoped commands:"],[776,"Admin; disables."],[803,"Admin; imports disabled."],[800,"Admin; nothing written."],[714,"Admin; prefer `status: \"archived\"`."],[652,"Admin; who did what, most recent first."],[66,"Admin."],[69,"Admin."],[74,"Admin."],[77,"Admin."],[83,"Admin."],[86,"Admin."],[304,"Admin."],[534,"Admin."],[537,"Admin."],[540,"Admin."],[546,"Admin."],[573,"Admin."],[631,"Admin."],[640,"Admin."],[773,"Admin."],[791,"Admin."],[794,"Admin."],[797,"Admin."],[637,"Admin. `{name, scopes, expiresInDays?}`."],[570,"Admin. `{value, description?}`."],[531,"Admin. Body: `name`, `workflowSlug`, `cron` or `runAt`, `timezone`, `input`, `enabled`."],[767,"Admin. Inline source or `workflow.bundleId`."],[567,"Admin. Names and metadata only."],[634,"Admin. Scope vocabulary, presets, defaults."],[1471,"Admins can export a workflow as a portable `.runyard-workflow.json` package file. It contains the workflow source bytes, metadata, requirements, and content hashes — never secret values."],[39,"Agent consumers — point AI agents at your Hub."],[40,"Agents, Skills & Knowledge"],[897,"Aliases are the same registry entries registered twice, so they always share\nthe canonical route's handler, auth, and scopes; in `openapi.json` each alias\ncarries `x-canonical-path`. Unversioned `/api/...` paths remain fully\nsupported — use whichever reads better. The legacy `/api/capabilities/*`\npaths are deprecated aliases of `/api/workflows/*` and get no `/api/v1` form;\nnew clients should say *workflow* everywhere."],[196,"All boards, default first."],[55,"All three are versioned and can be individually enabled/disabled."],[46,"Alongside workflows, the Hub maintains a shared catalog of reusable building blocks. They live in the database, are readable by any authenticated token, and are edited only by admins — so every workflow on the Hub draws from the same curated set."],[95,"An **approval** is a declared question with a declared consequence, presented to a human as a card in the web app, over Telegram, or through the API/MCP. Cards can hold a run before it executes (`waiting_approval`), pause a workflow mid-run at an engine gate, or simply record a decision. A run held on an approval waits indefinitely — waiting never fails it."],[1011,"An approval is a declared question with a declared consequence. Cards carry an *ask* — who is asked, what approving does, and why a human is needed — and every surface renders that stored ask verbatim. A run held on a card sits in `waiting_approval` and is never failed or age-reaped for waiting."],[111,"An ask without both `action` and `reason` is treated as absent; such cards fall back to a heuristic ask explicitly marked `derived: true`, so a guessed question is never presented as an authored one."],[353,"An invalid budget is rejected with `400 budget_invalid` at creation (and surfaces as a preflight blocker in negotiation) — a requested cap is never silently dropped."],[1151,"And the runner unit (`deploy/runyard-runner.service`):"],[972,"Answer questions: `input` is shallow-merged (a `null` value deletes a key; `replaceInput: true` replaces it), then re-preflighted"],[105,"Any ad-hoc approval raised via the API."],[205,"Any subset; `slug` is immutable."],[711,"Any subset; move lanes by setting `status`."],[45,"API & MCP"],[94,"API & MCP"],[154,"API & MCP"],[259,"API & MCP"],[381,"API & MCP"],[424,"API & MCP"],[507,"API & MCP"],[551,"API & MCP"],[581,"API & MCP"],[658,"API & MCP"],[734,"API & MCP"],[846,"API groups and `/api/v1` aliases"],[1037,"Applied as a deny with your note attached; the workflow's own deny path decides what happens next."],[1038,"Applied as a deny; the workflow's deny path decides what happens next."],[88,"Approval cards - kinds, the ask contract, resolutions, timed approvals with fallbacks, and per-kind consequences."],[251,"Approval cards carry `deepLink` (the card) and `deepLinkRun` (the linked run), and their `context` includes workflow and run deep links."],[1009,"Approval cards with buttons"],[1321,"Approval gating"],[240,"Approval inbox / one card."],[612,"Approval inboxes and bots that only decide."],[87,"Approvals"],[849,"Approvals"],[1077,"Approvals"],[1245,"Approvals"],[38,"Approvals — put human checkpoints in front of dangerous work."],[1001,"Approvals and Telegram"],[1048,"Approvals are blocking by default: with no timer configured, nothing happens until someone decides, and a linked run is held open indefinitely."],[646,"Approvals-scoped Telegram session."],[1028,"Approve"],[959,"Approve — a held run is released"],[622,"Approving from Telegram uses `POST /api/auth/telegram-webapp&#x60;, which verifies Telegram's signed init data against the configured bot and allowlisted users, then issues a session scoped to **`approvals` only** — narrower than any token session. A Telegram session can list and resolve approval cards but cannot start runs or touch admin surfaces."],[1247,"Artifacts"],[831,"Ask the Hub's administrator for a scoped access token (admins issue them from the Connect tab or `POST /api/tokens`). Agents typically need `api` and/or `mcp` — nothing more. Send it as `Authorization: Bearer <token>` on every HTTP call, or configure it for the MCP server. Never ask for or expect the bootstrap/admin token."],[1267,"Assistant"],[689,"Attach runs three ways:"],[946,"Audit log (admin)"],[815,"Auth"],[809,"Auth expectations"],[843,"Authenticate, discover, and drive workflow runs over the Runyard Hub's HTTP API."],[844,"Authentication"],[1431,"Authoring workflows"],[37,"Authoring workflows — create your own workflows over the API or MCP."],[101,"Autonomous recovery gave up; a human records how to proceed."],[1210,"Back this directory up. The runner workspace, by contrast, is disposable\nscratch space — outputs and event traces are uploaded to the Hub as artifacts."],[575,"Bearer-token authentication, the scope vocabulary and presets (including read-only), the bootstrap token, and how browser and Telegram sessions work."],[460,"Before anything is enqueued, Runyard can run a **deterministic preflight**: schema checks on required input fields, runner/tag availability, secret presence, hook eligibility, and workflow source resolution. The result is `ready`, `needs_input` (with `questions[]` the caller can answer), or `blocked` (with `blockers[]` only an operator can fix), plus warnings, suggested defaults, and a `nextAction` hint."],[1175,"Bind address (default `127.0.0.1`)"],[199,"Board + lanes with per-lane ticket counts + the decorated work items in scope."],[150,"Boards"],[717,"Body: `{ runId }`."],[720,"Body: `{ runId }`."],[578,"Bootstrap token"],[1007,"Bot setup"],[1440,"Both operations require an admin-scoped token."],[643,"Browser session bootstrap (rate-limited)."],[579,"Browser sessions"],[330,"Budgets"],[349,"Budgets are hard stops, not advisories:"],[805,"Building agents on Runyard"],[1299,"Builds and pushes GHCR `hub` and `runner` container images behind the same two gates, and records both image digests as a release artifact."],[119,"By default a card is blocking: nothing happens until someone decides. Supplying `timeoutMs` or `timeoutAt` at creation makes it a **timed approval**:"],[393,"By default the runner executes workflows directly on its host. Setting `RUNNER_SANDBOX=bubblewrap` on the runner wraps each workflow *launch* in a generated Bubblewrap (`bwrap`) sandbox: the run's workspace is the only writable mount (bound at the same path inside and out), system directories are bound read-only, and the child gets a fresh workspace-local `HOME` — the host home directory, with its keys and credentials, is never mounted. Polling and control commands stay outside the sandbox. Installing `bwrap` is the deployer's responsibility; the runner verifies at startup that the sandbox actually works before claiming runs."],[929,"Cancel; re-queue with same/edited input; merge a successful isolated run into its target branch"],[189,"Cancelling is already an operator act."],[677,"Cannot progress without a specific intervention (`blockedReason` says which)."],[879,"Canonical"],[379,"Capacity and pool"],[331,"Capture paths: what is metered today"],[1023,"Cards are posted to the configured chat with inline buttons (see below)."],[1070,"Cards can deep-link into the Hub as a Telegram WebApp. `POST /api/auth/telegram-webapp` exchanges the WebApp's signed init data for a browser session that is limited to the `approvals` scope — a Telegram identity can review and resolve approval cards, and nothing else. Full app access always requires a real access token."],[47,"Catalog"],[1263,"Catalog"],[1450,"Catalog grouping (for example `Examples`, `Operations`)."],[1060,"Chat (group or DM) where approval cards are posted."],[1391,"Check run diagnostics; fix workflow config or runner setup."],[1279,"CI pipeline"],[433,"Claimed by a runner, not yet started."],[1159,"claims runs and executes them; workspace volum