ed branches (`main`, `master`) are refused — merging to the default branch stays behind explicit run promotion."],[811,"Push instead of poll: response endpoints"],[1295,"Pushed `v*` tags"],[1298,"Pushed `v*` tags"],[526,"Query: `cron`, `timezone`."],[1122,"Quick install (host bootstrap)"],[11,"Quickstart"],[852,"Rate limits"],[667,"Raw ask, idea, bug, or product need."],[974,"Re-preflight and enqueue the real run only when ready — `202` with `{run, draft}`"],[1397,"Re-run; if recurring, raise the workflow's time budget or shrink the job."],[1388,"Read the run logs for the gate output; fix the underlying work and re-run."],[1406,"Read the run output and the linked approval/escalation card."],[57,"Reading any catalog requires only an authenticated token. Creating and updating entries requires the `admin` scope — the catalogs are part of the Hub's trusted configuration, like secrets and hook profiles."],[1111,"Reads available to any token: `runyard runners` (runner pool), `runyard agents`,\n`runyard skills`, `runyard knowledge -q <query>`, `runyard hooks [--workflow <slug>]`, and `runyard hook describe|validate <slug>`. Secrets have\nno CLI subcommand — manage them in the web UI, over the\nAPI (`PUT /api/secrets/:key`), or with the MCP `set_secret` tool."],[872,"Reads such as listing runs, workflows, or artifacts require any authenticated\ntoken. A token with only the `read` scope is therefore read-only: it can\ninspect everything non-admin but every create/update/delete/run/approve call\nfails with `403`. A request with no valid token gets\n`401 {\"error\": \"unauthorized\"}`; a token missing a required scope gets:"],[599,"Reads such as listing runs, workflows, runners, or schedules need only an authenticated token, whatever its scopes. Runner lifecycle endpoints additionally enforce **run ownership**: only the runner token that claimed a run (or an admin) may report on it."],[431,"Ready for a matching runner to claim."],[1293,"Real bubblewrap + AppArmor gate on Ubuntu 24.04: installs bwrap, loads the repo's AppArmor profile via the same script operators run, then runs the sandbox suites with `RUNYARD_REQUIRE_BWRAP=1` so the smoke test fails rather than skips."],[810,"Recommended agent etiquette"],[1219,"Recommended agent flow"],[335,"Records fold into the run's persisted aggregate the moment they arrive:"],[1042,"Records that the run should be left as it ended."],[1041,"Records that the workflow or input needs fixing; your note is the guidance."],[1040,"Records your go-ahead on the card; the run is not restarted — re-run it from the run page."],[54,"Reference resources — documents or links with a type, body/URL, and tags — searchable with `?q=` / `search_knowledge`."],[746,"References into the shared catalog."],[938,"Registered runners, heartbeat state, capacity, pool summary"],[377,"Registration, heartbeat, claim"],[1030,"Reject"],[961,"Reject — a held run is cancelled (never failed)"],[1107,"Related: `runyard workflow versions <workflow>` lists SHAs seen across runs and\n`runyard workflow rollback <workflow> <sha>` re-runs pinned to a prior SHA\n(`--from-run <id>` links it to the run being rolled back)."],[1029,"Request changes"],[963,"Request changes with a comment; the run is cancelled so it can be re-run with new input"],[1135,"Requirement"],[1121,"Requirements"],[422,"Reruns and promotion"],[868,"Resolve approval cards (approve / reject / request changes) and create them"],[1047,"Resolved cards keep the decision in their `resolution` field (`approved`, `rejected`, `changes_requested`) plus how it was decided (`resolvedVia`: human, fallback timer, engine, policy, or system)."],[1004,"Resolving a card"],[596,"Resolving and creating approval cards only — the narrow scope for approval surfaces."],[149,"Resolving approvals requires the `api`, `mcp`, or `approvals` scope; Telegram WebApp sessions are approvals-scoped by design (see Tokens & scopes)."],[423,"Response endpoints"],[50,"Reusable agent *roles*: a slug, name, description, instructions, a tool list, linked skill slugs, and tags. A role captures \"how this kind of agent should behave\" once, instead of restating it per workflow."],[1127,"Reverse proxy"],[170,"Review stays human-controlled."],[1155,"Role"],[213,"Route"],[210,"Route grammar"],[913,"Run a workflow: `{input, executionMode, negotiate?}`"],[273,"Run an allowlisted absolute command with declared, typed arguments — never a shell."],[222,"Run artifacts tab."],[948,"Run counts by status, recent activity, attention items"],[348,"Run creation accepts an optional hard spend ceiling — as a top-level `budget` field or `input.budget`, on direct runs, negotiated runs, drafts, schedules, endpoint submissions, and reruns (reruns inherit the previous run's budget unless overridden):"],[218,"Run detail."],[850,"Run drafts"],[1241,"Run drafts"],[1031,"Run hold (default / `custom`)"],[387,"Run lifecycle reports (`start`, events, `complete`, `fail`, artifact upload) are restricted to the runner that owns the run: the Hub checks the claiming token's identity, so one runner's token cannot touch another runner's runs."],[216,"Run list (also the home view)."],[220,"Run logs tab."],[919,"Run status, outputs, error, response-delivery state"],[1346,"Run workflows and read runs over HTTP."],[252,"Run-creating responses (`run_workflow`, schedule run-now, draft submit) include link objects for following the run — its status, events, and artifacts endpoints."],[1376,"Runner agent auth expired"],[1202,"Runner display name and capability tags"],[246,"Runner health and pool."],[1143,"Runner hosts additionally need the Smithers engine and at least one authenticated\nagent CLI (`claude`, `codex`, or `pi`) on `PATH` — see the CLI guide\nfor `runyard runner setup`."],[615,"Runner machines. Keep separate from human tokens."],[402,"Runner protocol (runner scope)."],[408,"Runner protocol; claims the next run."],[411,"Runner protocol; run ownership enforced."],[405,"Runner protocol."],[1322,"Runner sandboxing"],[1080,"Runner setup"],[1355,"Runner tokens are additionally subject to **run-ownership checks**: a run's lifecycle endpoints (`start`, `events`, `complete`, `fail`, artifact upload) only accept the runner that owns the run, or an admin. One compromised runner token cannot report on, or interfere with, another runner's work."],[366,"Runner-observed engine telemetry"],[1196,"Runner-scoped access token minted on the Hub"],[1190,"Runner:"],[375,"Runners"],[1249,"Runners"],[388,"Runners advertise **tags** (for example `local` on a workstation, `vps` on a shared remote pool). Two things match runs to runners:"],[466,"Runners append structured **events** as the run progresses; `GET /api/runs/{id}/events/stream` serves them live over SSE and `GET /api/runs/{id}/timeline` merges status transitions, events, and artifacts into one ascending feed (with `since`/`limit` paging). Log lines are at `/logs`, a condensed log summary and diagnostics at `/diagnostics`, and uploaded **artifacts** (outputs, traces, files) at `/artifacts`, downloadable by artifact id."],[1359,"Runners can execute workflow processes inside a bubblewrap sandbox (`RUNNER_SANDBOX=bubblewrap`), and the repo ships a narrow AppArmor profile (`deploy/apparmor/install.sh`) that grants unprivileged user-namespace creation to bwrap on Ubuntu 24.04+ kernels that restrict it. This is not on faith: CI runs a `sandbox-smoke` job on every push that installs bubblewrap, loads the profile through the same operator install script, and runs the sandbox suites with `RUNYARD_REQUIRE_BWRAP=1` so the real-bwrap smoke test fails instead of silently skipping if the path regresses."],[28,"Runners execute workflows with the Smithers engine, so a runner host needs `bun`, `smithers`, and at least one authenticated agent CLI (`claude`, `codex`, or `pi`) on its PATH."],[383,"Runners speak a small machine protocol authenticated with **runner-scoped tokens** (see Tokens & scopes):"],[399,"Runners, heartbeat state, capacity, slots, pool summary."],[1237,"Running"],[804,"Running a workflow (`POST /api/workflows/{id}/run`, `run_workflow`) and preflighting it are covered on the Runs page."],[1123,"Running from source"],[413,"Runs"],[1239,"Runs (observe)"],[454,"Runs also meter the model calls they consume: per-call usage records stream as `run.usage` events and aggregate onto the run as `usage` (`totalTokens`, `costMicros`, `byModel`, ...), and run creation accepts an optional `budget: { maxTokens?, maxCostMicros? }` hard ceiling. Budgeted runs additionally carry a computed `budgetStatus` (spent vs limit, remaining, percent used, `nearLimit` at 80%) in list and detail payloads. See Usage metering & budgets for the data model, the fleet rollup (`GET /api/usage/summary`), the metering gateway, and budget enforcement."],[1420,"Runs failing with provider auth errors usually mean the runner's `codex`/`claude` CLI login lapsed. On hosts with `REAUTH_ENABLED=1`, an admin can trigger re-auth from the web app (runner card → Re-auth): the Hub surfaces a verification URL and user code, and never token material. Otherwise, log in on the runner host directly (`codex login`, `claude setup-token`)."],[153,"Runs move tickets"],[364,"Runs that select `metering: \"gateway\"` with the pi harness (`piModel`, `piBaseUrl`, `piApiKeyEnv`)"],[1131,"Runyard is a self-hosted control plane for agent runs. A deployment has a small,\nfixed shape:"],[4,"Runyard is a self-hosted control plane for agent runs. Agents and humans trigger workflows over MCP, the CLI, the HTTP API, or the web app; runners execute those workflows with the Smithers engine; and the Hub stores the durable record of everything that happened — runs, logs, events, artifacts, approvals, and knowledge. A run started from a chat agent, a cron schedule, or a terminal all leaves the same auditable trail in the same place."],[314,"Runyard is a self-hosted control plane for agent runs. You install **workflows** into a catalog, start **runs** of those workflows from the API, MCP, web app, or a **schedule**, and **runners** claim and execute them. The durable company asks those runs work on are **work items** — tickets on the Work board. Anything that needs a human decision surfaces as an **approval** card, sensitive values live in the encrypted **secrets** store, and optional side effects after a run are handled by admin-defined **hooks**. Access is governed by scoped **tokens**, and every page in the Hub is a shareable **deep link**."],[6,"Runyard is API-first by construction. Every HTTP route the Hub serves is declared in a single API surface registry; the OpenAPI document is generated from it and the MCP tool list is parity-tested against it. The web app is an ordinary API client with no privileged endpoints — anything it can show or do is equally available over the API and MCP, so a third-party client built on those surfaces loses nothing."],[5,"Runyard is designed as one private deployment per company. Your Hub holds your workflow catalog, your secrets, your runners, and your history; nothing about your deployment is published to a shared service, and the only outbound call the Hub makes is a passive read of the public GitHub Releases API to check for updates. Operators, teammates, and their agents all authenticate to the same Hub with scoped access tokens."],[1325,"Runyard is one private deployment per company, and the security model follows from that: a small, deliberate unauthenticated surface; scoped bearer tokens for everything else; secrets encrypted at rest and never echoed; and approval gates in front of dangerous work."],[552,"Runyard keeps reusable credentials (API keys, deploy tokens) in an **encrypted secret store** on the Hub. Values are encrypted at rest, and the API is deliberately one-way: you can list secret *names and metadata*, set a value, and delete one — **values are never returned** by any list or read endpoint, to any scope."],[1153,"Runyard publishes two environment-agnostic images to GHCR:"],[1283,"Runyard releases are semver git tags (`vX.Y.Z`). The version in `package.json` is the single source of truth and flows to `/api/version`, the OpenAPI document, the CLI, and the update checker."],[1314,"Runyard ships a repo-agnostic `docs-update` workflow that keeps documentation honest against each release. When a release is published, a GitHub Actions step triggers it on the project's own Hub through an authenticated workflow endpoint (`release-docs-update`); the workflow inspects only the git diff between the previous and new release tags — never the whole repository — and reports proposed documentation updates. In its opt-in `apply` mode it edits docs in an isolated worktree branch instead, and that branch reaches the target branch only through a human-approved run promotion. The repository, docs path, docs framework, and file-selection rules are all workflow inputs, so any repo can adopt it."],[813,"Runyard treats agents as first-class API consumers. This page covers how a client discovers what a Hub can do, what it may rely on, and how to be a good citizen."],[509,"Runyard uses standard **5-field cron** (`minute hour day-of-month month day-of-week`) with ranges (`a-b`), lists (`a,b,c`), steps (`*/n`, `a-b/n`), month/weekday names (`jan..dec`, `sun..sat`), and the aliases `@yearly`, `@monthly`, `@weekly`, `@daily`, `@hourly`. There is no seconds field — the Hub ticks at minute granularity."],[1292,"Same"],[380,"Sandboxing"],[501,"Schedules"],[1243,"Schedules"],[242,"Schedules / one schedule."],[585,"Scope"],[857,"Scope"],[1343,"Scope"],[576,"Scopes"],[602,"Scopes"],[1318,"Scopes"],[1183,"Secret for browser session cookies. Required in production; in dev a generated value is persisted to the data dir"],[553,"Secret names are env-var-safe identifiers, because that is exactly how they are delivered. The whole feature is gated on the store being enabled (an encryption key configured on the Hub); when it is not, secret-dependent runs and hooks report that configuration is required instead of failing obscurely."],[1064,"Secret Telegram echoes back so the Hub can verify webhook calls."],[547,"Secrets"],[1253,"Secrets"],[1319,"Secrets"],[558,"Secrets never appear in run events, logs, or the run record."],[1374,"Secrets not configured"],[1315,"Security model"],[1166,"See `deploy/dstack/README.md` in the repository for the full contract."],[853,"See also"],[1116,"See the MCP guide for clients and options."],[249,"Segments are URL-encoded, so ids and slugs with special characters remain valid links. Some tabs accept aliases (for example `visual` for `graph`, `source` for `code`)."],[332,"Selecting gateway metering"],[257,"Selecting hooks per run"],[275,"Selection is explicit and two-sided:"],[1281,"Self-update for deployments"],[855,"Send an access token as a bearer token on every request:"],[1468,"Send the changed definition — again with source bytes inline — via `PATCH /api/workflows/{id}` or `update_workflow`. The Hub publishes a **new** bundle version and repoints `workflow.bundleId`; existing bundles are never mutated, so historical runs keep an exact record of what they executed. Identical bytes are deduplicated by hash rather than republished."],[152,"Shape"],[232,"Source code tab."],[750,"Source configuration — most importantly `workflow.bundleId`, plus options like `hooks.allowedProfiles` for post-run hooks and `secrets` for secret delivery."],[359,"Source label"],[1464,"Source language, defaults to `tsx`."],[779,"Source, metadata, sections, graph."],[1444,"Stable identifier used in URLs, the CLI, and MCP (`runyard run <slug>`)."],[829,"Start every session with `get_menu` (or `GET /api/menu`), then `describe_workflow` for anything you intend to run."],[860,"Start runs, preflight, drafts, rerun/cancel/promote, create approvals"],[1409,"Start with diagnostics and logs."],[236,"Start-a-run form."],[1336,"Static, generic agent discovery document."],[819,"Static, generic orientation for agents: what Runyard is, its tool names, the run path. It deliberately contains nothing deployment-specific and points at the authenticated menu."],[426,"Status"],[664,"Status"],[977,"Status"],[91,"Status and resolution"],[686,"Status moves happen two ways, both recorded in ticket history as `work_item.status_changed` events (alongside run link/unlink events and field edits): explicit `PATCH`es by a human or agent, and automatic moves by linked runs where the mapping is reliable — a run going live puts the ticket in `running`, a held run parks it in `waiting`, a succeeded run sends it to `review`, a failed run parks it in `blocked` with a reason. Automated moves are attributed to the run (`actor: \"run:run_…\"`); see Boards for the full mapping."],[441,"Stopped by an operator or a rejected approval — a human \"no\" is a decision, not a failure."],[559,"Stored secret values are additionally scrubbed from run output and artifacts before they are persisted."],[1424,"Structured diagnosis + log summary for a run (`get_run_diagnostics`)."],[925,"Structured events, log lines, diagnostics + log summary"],[1354,"Superscope: satisfies every scope requirement and gates all mutation of workflows, secrets, tokens, schedules, hooks, and updates."],[1223,"Supported `--client` values: `claude-code`, `claude-desktop`, `codex`,\n`cursor`, `windsurf`, `gemini`, `vscode`. Each writes the appropriate config\nfile (for example `.mcp.json` for Claude Code, `~/.codex/config.toml` for\nCodex, `.vscode/mcp.json` for VS Code) and prints how to activate it."],[814,"Surface"],[1012,"Surface"],[1303,"Surface"],[1421,"Surface"],[1124,"systemd"],[744,"Tags a runner must advertise to be assigned a run."],[1456,"Tags a runner must advertise to claim runs (for example `[\"smithers\"]`)."],[378,"Tags and execution modes"],[142,"Takes an approval id, not a run id."],[1096,"Target a specific runner location tag"],[1022,"Telegram"],[1006,"Telegram integration"],[1375,"Telegram not delivering"],[1010,"Telegram WebApp login"],[580,"Telegram WebApp sessions"],[443,"Terminal failure; see failure classes below."],[1382,"Terminal failures carry a class so you know whether to fix input, config, or infrastructure:"],[342,"Terminal response-endpoint payloads — `usage`, `budget`, and `budgetStop` fields, so delegated callers can bill or cap against real consumption."],[444,"Terminal states are final: late reports racing a terminal state are absorbed idempotently rather than overwriting the first decision."],[180,"The \"Needs decision\" lane."],[1015,"The **Approvals** view lists pending cards with their ask, consequences, and buttons."],[1227,"The `--remote <name>` argument, resolved against the saved remotes in\n`~/.runyard/config.json` (written by `runyard login`)"],[987,"The `422`/`409` bodies are returned by `run` with `negotiate: true` and by\ndraft `submit`; they are structured responses, not opaque failures — answer the\nquestions and retry."],[1083,"The `runyard` CLI is a thin client of the Hub's HTTP API. It talks\nto one or more Hubs (\"remotes\"), starts and tails workflow runs, resolves\napprovals, and can set up and start a runner on the local machine."],[500,"The `start`/`complete`/`fail`/event-append and artifact-upload endpoints under `/api/runs/{id}` are the runner protocol (runner-scoped tokens, run ownership enforced) — see Runners."],[1399,"The agent's output failed schema validation."],[127,"The API exposes these as `whatHappensIfApproved` / `whatHappensIfRejected` / `whatHappensIfChangesRequested` / `whatHappensIfIgnored` in each card's `context`, alongside the ask, the linked run, and deep links."],[250,"The API hands these links back so agents and integrations can point humans at the right screen without building URLs themselves:"],[808,"The API-first guarantee"],[90,"The ask contract"],[1152,"The bootstrap script installs these for you, retargeted to your install\ndirectory, env-file location, and node binary. Secrets live in the\n`EnvironmentFile`s (mode `0600`), never in the units."],[1058,"The bot's API token."],[277,"The caller selects profiles per run with `input.postRunHooks: [\"publish-docs\", …]`."],[390,"The caller's execution intent: `executionMode: \"local\" | \"remote\" | \"auto\"` (optionally a specific `runnerLocation`). `remote` targets the shared remote/VPS pool (default location `vps`); `auto` takes any matching runner."],[310,"The catalog"],[727,"The catalog unit of Runyard - versioned definitions with schemas, immutable source bundles, and portable packages."],[1086,"The CLI stores named remotes (Hub URL + token) in `~/.runyard/config.json`\n(mode `0600`). Every command accepts global options `--url`, `--token`,\n`--remote <name>`, and `--json` (machine-readable output)."],[354,"The CLI takes budgets as flags: `runyard run research --max-tokens 200000 --max-cost 2` (`--max-cost` is US dollars; the same flags work on `runyard preflight`)."],[825,"The complete MCP tool set (parity-tested against the API surface). Connect with `runyard mcp install` or the `runyard-mcp` stdio server."],[1470,"The corresponding MCP tools are `get_workflow_source`, `list_workflow_bundles`, and `get_workflow_bundle` (which does include the source). You can also publish a bundle directly with `POST /api/workflow-bundles` / `publish_workflow_bundle` and reference it by `workflow.bundleId`, but prefer inline source — the Hub publishes the bundle for you."],[106,"The creator of a card states the ask up front, and every surface renders it verbatim:"],[1228,"The current saved remote"],[1036,"The decision is applied to the paused workflow on the runner and it resumes past the gate."],[548,"The encrypted secret store - admin-managed, listable by name only, delivered to runs at claim time and never returned by the API."],[1084,"The fastest path is the install script served by your own Hub, which downloads\nthe CLI tarball from the same instance (`/cli.tgz`), installs `runyard` and\n`runyard-mcp` into `~/.local/bin`, and logs you in:"],[329,"The fleet rollup: `GET /api/usage/summary`"],[696,"The fold is derived, never stored: explicit `node.*` lifecycle events win; an unresolved `engine.approval.waiting` parks its step in `waiting`; the run's own terminal status closes the books (succeeded finishes unfinished active steps, cancelled cancels them, a failure-terminal status fails the step the run died on). When no source graph exists the flow degrades to an event-derived stepper rather than hiding observed work. The ticket detail renders this as the flow view for the active or latest linked run."],[822,"The full HTTP surface, generated from the Hub's API surface registry — it cannot drift from the routes the server actually registers."],[1044,"The gated side effect is allowed to run."],[1284,"The GitHub Actions pipeline (`.github/workflows/release.yml` and `images.yml`) has four jobs:"],[1032,"The held run is released to the queue and executes."],[292,"The hook did not run."],[1053,"The Hub can post approval cards to a Telegram chat and accept decisions from the buttons on them."],[1167,"The Hub is a single HTTP listener; any TLS-terminating proxy that forwards **all\npaths** to the Hub port works. With Caddy:"],[1148,"The Hub listens on `127.0.0.1:43117` by default. Start a runner in a second\nprocess:"],[1138,"The Hub uses the built-in `node:sqlite` module (started with `--experimental-sqlite`)"],[828,"The live, private catalog: workflows with schemas, execution modes, runner pool state, and ready-to-use CLI/MCP invocations."],[376,"The machines that claim and execute runs via the Smithers engine - registration, tags, capacity, health, and sandboxing."],[419,"The needs-attention queue"],[1218,"The parity guarantee"],[1160,"The portable base stack is `docker-compose.yml` at the repo root:"],[511,"The preview returns a human-readable description plus the next fire instants — nothing is created."],[288,"The profile cannot execute — typically missing named secrets or a disabled secret store."],[290,"The profile was not eligible for